The author Robert introduces this remarkable story.
A friend told Robert about two scuba divers who recently discovered a World War II German U-boat off of New Jersey.
Robert contacted the divers, John Chatterton and Richie Kohler.
John and Richie liked to scuba dive for fun on the weekends.
Robert met John and Richie at John's house to hear their story.
John and Richie told Robert the story over 14 hours.
Their story entailed discovery, mystery, rivalries, obsession, and bravery.
Robert decided to turn this story into a writing opportunity.
Robert attests that everything is true and accurate.
Robert spent endless hours conducting research and interviews.
John and Richie commented about the depth of shipwreck diving.
At these depths, sometimes all the divers can see are shadows.
Robert decided to call the book Shadow Divers.
The book starts out in September 1991 in New Jersey.
Bill Nagle waits for a fisherman to give him information on how to find a shipwreck.
Bill was 40-years-old in 1991.
Bill was the captain of the "Seeker," a charter diving boat that he operated from Brielle, New Jersey.
Bill built the Seeker to take divers to the most dangerous wrecks in the Atlantic Ocean.
When Bill was in his 20s, he became a legend of diving shipwrecks.
In the 1970s and 1980s, shipwreck diving was a new sport.
The equipment had changed very little since it was invented in the 1940s.
Bill was a diver who always pushed the limits.
He preferred undiscovered wrecks and regularly dove below 200 feet deep.
Bill had spent some time diving the popular wreck the "Andrea Doria."
This is a shipwreck from 1956.
Many men have died while exploring this wreck.
Bill's goal was to recover the bell of the Andrea Doria.
Bill bought a dive boat (the original Seeker), recruited five divers, and successfully discovered the bell.
After this, Bill decided to open a charter business.
By 1991, Bill was endangering his business by excessive drinking.
He spent much of his time at a bar called the Harbor Inn (aka the Horrible Inn).
Since shipwrecks were common places to find fish, many wrecks were discovered by fishing boat captains.
These captains kept the wreck locations secret from competitors.
The fishing captains would write the coordinates of the sites in a private journal.
Shipwreck divers would also keep the location of wrecks a secret.
Occasionally, divers and fishermen would trade numbers.
This is what Bill was waiting to do at the beginning of the chapter.
Bill met a fishing captain named Skeets at the Harbor Inn. Skeets told Bill about a spot 60 miles offshore.
There seemed to be a very large object over 200 feet deep here.
Skeets offered to trade the coordinates for the spot in exchange for a wreck he knew Bill could locate.
Skeets warned Bill that his site is in a very dangerous place with strong currents.
This did not worry Bill.
Bill contacted John Chatterton.
Bill had met John years ago during a charter trip to the Texas Tower.
A man died on this trip, and John offered to retrieve the body.
Bill respected John after this.
Bill asked John if he wanted to help explore the mystery wreck.
Bill and John enlisted twelve more divers willing to cover expenses.
On September 2nd, 1991, the divers headed toward the coordinates of the mystery wreck.
